[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] Web Application Security Tools are specialized tools for working with HTTP traffic, e.g., Web application firewalls.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] Different approaches will find different subsets of the security vulnerabilities lurking in an application and are most effective at different times in the software lifecycle.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] They each represent different tradeoffs of time, effort, cost and vulnerabilities found.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] The Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) provides free and open resources.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] It is led by a non-profit called The OWASP Foundation.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] The OWASP Top 10 - 2017 results from recent research based on comprehensive data compiled from over 40 partner organizations.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] This data revealed approximately 2.3 million vulnerabilities across over 50,000 applications.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] The OWASP Top 10 Proactive Controls 2024 is a list of security techniques every software architect and developer should know and heed.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] Security testing techniques scour for vulnerabilities or security holes in applications.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] These vulnerabilities leave applications open to exploitation.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] Ideally, security testing is implemented throughout the entire software development life cycle (SDLC) so that vulnerabilities may be addressed in a timely and thorough manner.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/application-security] There are many kinds of automated tools for identifying vulnerabilities in applications.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/intrusion-detection-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet is focused on providing developers with concentrated guidance on building application logging mechanisms, especially related to security logging.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Many systems enable network device, operating system, web server, mail server and database server logging, but often custom application event logging is missing, disabled or poorly configured.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] It provides much greater insight than infrastructure logging alone.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Web application (e.g. web site or web service) logging is much more than having web server logs enabled (e.g. using Extended Log File Format).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logging should be consistent within the application, consistent across an organization's application portfolio and use industry standards where relevant, so the logged event data can be consumed, correlated, analyzed and managed by a wide variety of systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logging should always be included for security events.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logs are invaluable data for both security and operational use cases.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Process monitoring, audit, and transaction logs/trails etc. are usually collected for different purposes than security event logging, and this often means they should be kept separate.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] The types of events and details collected will tend to be different.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] For example a PCIDSS audit log will contain a chronological record of activities to provide an independently verifiable trail that permits reconstruction, review and examination to determine the original sequence of attributable transactions.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] It is important not to log too much, or too little.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Use knowledge of the intended purposes to guide what, when and how much.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] The remainder of this cheat sheet primarily discusses security event logging.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] The application itself has access to a wide range of information events that should be used to generate log entries.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Thus, the primary event data source is the application code itself.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] The application has the most information about the user (e.g. identity, roles, permissions) and the context of the event (target, action, outcomes), and often this data is not available to either infrastructure devices, or even closely-related applications.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] The degree of confidence in the event information has to be considered when including event data from systems in a different trust zone.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Data may be missing, modified, forged, replayed and could be malicious – it must always be treated as untrusted data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider how the source can be verified, and how integrity and non-repudiation can be enforced.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Applications commonly write event log data to the file system or a database (SQL or NoSQL).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Applications installed on desktops and on mobile devices may use local storage and local databases, as well as sending data to remote storage.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Your selected framework may limit the available choices.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] All types of applications may send event data to remote systems (instead of or as well as more local storage).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] This could be a centralized log collection and management system (e.g.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] SIEM or SEM) or another application elsewhere.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider whether the application can simply send its event stream, unbuffered, to stdout, for management by the execution environment.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider separate files/tables for extended event information such as error stack traces or a record of HTTP request and response headers and bodies.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] The level and content of security monitoring, alerting, and reporting needs to be set during the requirements and design stage of projects, and should be proportionate to the information security risks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] This can then be used to define what should be logged.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] There is no one size fits all solution, and a blind checklist approach can lead to unnecessary "alarm fog" that means real problems go undetected.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Each log entry needs to include sufficient information for the intended subsequent monitoring and analysis.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] It could be full content data, but is more likely to be an extract or just summary properties.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] The application logs must record "when, where, who and what" for each event.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] For more information on these, see the "other" related articles listed at the end, especially the comprehensive article by Anton Chuvakin and Gunnar Peterson.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Never log data unless it is legally sanctioned.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] For example, intercepting some communications, monitoring employees, and collecting some data without consent may all be illegal.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Never exclude any events from "known" users such as other internal systems, "trusted" third parties, search engine robots, uptime/process and other remote monitoring systems, pen testers, auditors.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] However, you may want to include a classification flag for each of these in the recorded data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider using personal data de-identification techniques such as deletion, scrambling or pseudonymization of direct and indirect identifiers where the individual's identity is not required, or the risk is considered too great.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] In some systems, sanitization can be undertaken post log collection, and prior to log display.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] It may be desirable to be able to alter the level of logging (type of events based on severity or threat level, amount of detail recorded).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] If your development framework supports suitable logging mechanisms, use or build upon that.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Otherwise, implement an application-wide log handler which can be called from other modules/components.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Document the interface referencing the organisation-specific event classification and description syntax requirements.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] If possible create this log handler as a standard module that can be thoroughly tested, deployed in multiple applications, and added to a list of approved and recommended modules.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Where possible, record data in a standard format, or at least ensure it can be exported/broadcast using an industry-standard format.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] In some cases, events may be relayed or collected together in intermediate points.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] In the latter some data may be aggregated or summarized before forwarding on to a central repository and analysis system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] As an example, the diagram below shows a service that provides business functionality to customers.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] We recommend creating a centralized system for collecting logs.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] There may be many such services, but all of them must securely collect logs in a centralized system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] For example, all external requests from users go through the API management service, see application in MIDDLEWARE 2 segment.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] As you can see in the image above, at the network level, the processes of saving and downloading logs require opening different network accesses (ports), arrows are highlighted in different colors.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Also, saving and downloading are performed by different applications.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Enable processes to detect whether logging has stopped, and to identify tampering or unauthorized access and deletion (see protection below).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] The logging mechanisms and collected event data must be protected from mis-use such as tampering in transit, and unauthorized access, modification and deletion once stored.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Logs may contain personal and other sensitive information, or the data may contain information regarding the application's code and logic.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] In addition, the collected information in the logs may itself have business value (to competitors, gossip-mongers, journalists and activists) such as allowing the estimate of revenues, or providing performance information about employees.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] This data may be held on end devices, at intermediate points, in centralized repositories and in archives and backups.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider whether parts of the data may need to be excluded, masked, sanitized, hashed, or encrypted during examination or extraction.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] See `NIST SP 800-92` Guide to Computer Security Log Management for more guidance.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Log data, temporary debug logs, and backups/copies/extractions, must not be destroyed before the duration of the required data retention period, and must not be kept beyond this time.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Legal, regulatory and contractual obligations may impact on these periods.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Because of their usefulness as a defense, logs may be a target of attacks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] See also OWASP Log Injection and CWE-117.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] A confidentiality attack enables an unauthorized party to access sensitive information stored in logs.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/logging-cheat-sheet] Which information should be modifiable by whom?
[src:threat-detection-appsec/runtime-application-self-protection] RASP can be integrated as a framework or module that runs in conjunction with a program's codes, libraries and system calls.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/runtime-application-self-protection] The technology can also be implemented as a virtualization.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/runtime-application-self-protection] RASP solutions can be deployed in two different ways: monitor or protection mode.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/runtime-application-self-protection] In monitor mode, the RASP solution reports on web application attacks but does not block any attack.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/runtime-application-self-protection] In protection mode, the RASP solution reports and blocks web application attacks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM tools can be implemented as software, hardware, or managed services.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems log security events and generate reports to meet regulatory frameworks such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] The integration of SIM and SEM within SIEM provides organizations with a centralized approach for monitoring security events and responding to threats in real-time.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] In recent years, SIEM has become increasingly incorporated into national cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] For instance, Executive Order 14028 signed in 2021 by U.S.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden mandates the use of SIEM technologies to improve incident detection and reporting in federal systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Compliance with these mandates is further reinforced by frameworks such as NIST SP 800-92, which outlines best practices for managing computer security logs.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms are aggregating and normalizing data not only from various Information Technology (IT) sources, but from production and manufacturing Operational Technology (OT) environments as well.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Initially, system logging was primarily used for troubleshooting and debugging.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] However, as operating systems and networks have grown more complex, so has the generation of system logs.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] The monitoring of system logs has also become increasingly common due to the rise of sophisticated cyberattacks and the need for compliance with regulatory frameworks, which mandate logging security controls within risk management frameworks (RMF).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Starting in the late 1970s, working groups began establishing criteria for managing auditing and monitoring programs, laying the groundwork for modern cybersecurity practices, such as insider threat detection and incident response.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] A key publication during this period was NIST’s Special Publication 500-19.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] In 2005, the term "SIEM" (Security Information and Event Management) was introduced by Gartner analysts Mark Nicolett and Amrit Williams.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems provide a single interface for gathering security data from information systems and presenting it as actionable intelligence.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] With the implementation of RMFs globally, auditing and monitoring have become central to information assurance and security.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Cybersecurity professionals now rely on logging data to perform real-time security functions, driven by governance models that incorporate these processes into analytical tasks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] As information assurance matured in the late 1990s and into the 2000s, the need to centralize system logs became apparent.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Centralized log management allows for easier oversight and coordination across networked systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden signed Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity," which established further logging requirements, including audit logging and endpoint protection, to enhance incident response capabilities.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] This order was a response to an increase in ransomware attacks targeting critical infrastructure.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] By reinforcing information assurance controls within RMFs, the order aimed to drive compliance and secure funding for cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Published in September 2006, the NIST SP 800-92 Guide to Computer Security Log Management serves as a key document within the NIST Risk Management Framework to guide what should be auditable.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] As indicated by the absence of the term "SIEM", the document was released before the widespread adoption of SIEM technologies.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Although the guide is not exhaustive due to rapid changes in technology since its publication, it remains relevant by anticipating industry growth.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] NIST is not the only source of guidance on regulatory mechanisms for auditing and monitoring, and many organizations are encouraged to adopt SIEM solutions rather than relying solely on host-based checks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Public and private organizations frequently reference NIST documents in their security policies.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 AU-2 Event Monitoring is a key security control that supports system auditing and ensures continuous monitoring for information assurance and cybersecurity operations.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions are typically employed as central tools for these efforts.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Federal systems categorized based on their impact on confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) have five specific logging requirements (AU-2 a-e) that must be met.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] While logging every action is possible, it is generally not recommended due to the volume of logs and the need for actionable security data.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] AU-2 provides a foundation for organizations to build a logging strategy that aligns with other controls.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 SI-4 System Monitoring outlines the requirements for monitoring systems, including detecting unauthorized access and tracking anomalies, malware, and potential attacks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] This security control specifies both the hardware and software requirements for detecting suspicious activities.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, NIST SP 800-53 RA-10 Threat Hunting, added in Revision 5, emphasizes proactive network defense by identifying threats that evade traditional controls.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions play a critical role in aggregating security information for threat hunting teams.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Together, AU-2, SI-4, and RA-10 demonstrate how NIST controls integrate into a comprehensive security strategy.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] These controls, supported by SIEM solutions, help ensure continuous monitoring, risk assessments, and in-depth defense mechanisms across federal and private networks.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] In practice many products in this area will have a mix of these functions, so there will often be some overlap – and many commercial vendors also promote their own terminology.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Oftentimes commercial vendors provide different combinations of these functionalities which tend to improve SIEM overall.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Log management alone doesn't provide real-time insights on network security, SEM on its own won't provide complete data for deep threat analysis.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] When SEM and log management are combined, more information is available for SIEM to monitor.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] A key focus is to monitor and help manage user and service privileges, directory services and other system-configuration changes; as well as providing log auditing and review and incident response.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM architectures may vary by vendor; however, generally, essential components comprise the SIEM engine.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] A basic SIEM infrastructure is depicted in the image to the right.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Computer security researcher Chris Kubecka identified the following SIEM use cases, presented at the hacking conference 28C3 (Chaos Communication Congress).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms support not only detection, but response too.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] The response can be manual or automated including AI based response.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems play a significant role in helping organizations meet regulatory compliance requirements by centralizing log collection, enabling real-time monitoring, and generating audit-ready reports.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, covered entities must implement audit controls that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to security incidents within 24 hours, a capability commonly provided by SIEM platforms.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data, with SIEM systems commonly used to aggregate and analyze the required log data across distributed environments.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires organizations to maintain audit trails for financial system access, and SIEM platforms provide the centralized logging and retention capabilities necessary to demonstrate compliance during audits.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems can have hundreds and thousands of correlation rules.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Some of these are simple, and some are more complex.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Once a correlation rule is triggered the system can take appropriate steps to mitigate a cyber attack.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Usually, this includes sending a notification to a user and then possibly limiting or even shutting down the system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Brute force detection is relatively straightforward.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Brute forcing relates to continually trying to guess a variable.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] It most commonly refers to someone trying to constantly guess your password - either manually or with a tool.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] However, it can refer to trying to guess URLs or important file locations on your system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] An automated brute force is easy to detect as someone trying to enter their password 60 times in a minute is impossible.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] When a user logs in to a system, generally speaking, it creates a timestamp of the event.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Alongside the time, the system may often record other useful information such as the device used, physical location, IP address, incorrect login attempts, etc.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] The more data is collected the more use can be gathered from it.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] For impossible travel, the system looks at the current and last login date/time and the difference between the recorded distances.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] If it deems it's not possible for this to happen, for example traveling hundreds of miles within a minute, then it will set off a warning.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Many employees and users are now using VPN services which may obscure physical location.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] This should be taken into consideration when setting up such a rule.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] The average user does not typically copy or move files on the system repeatedly.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Thus, any excessive file copying on a system could be attributed to an attacker wanting to cause harm to an organization.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Unfortunately, it's not as simple as stating someone has gained access to your network illegally and wants to steal confidential information.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] It could also be an employee looking to sell company information, or they could just want to take home some files for the weekend.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Monitoring network traffic against unusual patterns that includes any threats or attacks ranging from DDOS to network scans.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Note SIEM can monitor data flow in the network and to detect and prevent potential data exfiltration efforts.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] In general dedicated Data loss prevention (DLP) take care about data loss prevention.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS (distributed denial of service) attack could cause significant damage to a company or organization.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS attack can not only take a website offline, it can also make a system weaker.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] With suitable correlation rules in place, a SIEM should trigger an alert at the start of the attack so that the company can take the necessary precautionary measures to protect vital systems.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] File integrity and change monitoring (FIM) is the process of monitoring the files on your system.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Unexpected changes in your system files will trigger an alert as it's a likely indication of a cyber attack.
[src:threat-detection-appsec/security-information-and-event-management] Some examples of customized rules to alert on event conditions involve user authentication rules, attacks detected and infections detected.
